<subSubSection pageNumber="784" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="784">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="784">Note:</emphasis>
Linnaeus included several different taxa within his concept of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="784">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubra">Q. rubra</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Although most early authors applied it to the northern red oak, Sargent (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="784">Rhodora</emphasis>
17: 39. 1915; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="784">l.c.</emphasis>
18: 45. 1916) argued that the name should be used for the species widely known as 
<taxonomicName authority="Michx. Others" authorityName="Michx. Others" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="falcata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="784">Q. falcata</emphasis>
Michx. Others
</taxonomicName>
(e.g. Svenson, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="784">l.c.</emphasis>
41: 521. 1941; 47: 298, 366. 1945; and Fernald (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="784">J. Arnold Arbor.</emphasis>
27: 391. 1946) disagreed but as a result of this divergence, some (e.g. Rehder in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="784">J. Arnold. Arbor.</emphasis>
19: 283. 1938) have treated the the name as a 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="784">nomen ambiguum.</emphasis>
However, as the name continues to be in use, the name is formally typified here in its traditional sense, that of the northern red oak.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
